---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { siteConfig } from '@/data/site';

const title = 'How to Start an LLC in Texas (2026 Guide)';
const description =
  'Step-by-step guide to forming an LLC in Texas. Learn about the $300 filing fee, registered agent requirements, franchise tax, and everything you need to start your Texas LLC.';
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#1e3a5f]/90 py-16 sm:py-20">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 text-center sm:px-6">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-white sm:text-4xl lg:text-5xl">
        How to Start an LLC in Texas
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm font-medium text-blue-200">Updated for 2026</p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-relaxed text-blue-100">
        Texas is one of the best states to form an LLC, with no state income tax, a $300 filing fee, and a business-friendly regulatory environment. Here is everything you need to know.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 py-12 sm:px-6 sm:py-16">

    <!-- Quick Facts -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">Texas LLC Quick Facts</h2>
        <div class="mt-4 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
          {[
            { label: 'Filing Fee', value: '$300' },
            { label: 'State Agency', value: 'Texas Secretary of State' },
            { label: 'Formation Document', value: 'Certificate of Formation' },
            { label: 'State Income Tax', value: 'None' },
            { label: 'Annual Report', value: 'No annual report required' },
            { label: 'Franchise Tax', value: 'Varies (see below)' },
          ].map((fact) => (
            <div class="rounded-lg bg-gray-50 p-3">
              <span class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-gray-500">{fact.label}</span>
              <p class="mt-1 text-sm font-bold text-gray-900">{fact.value}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
        <p class="mt-4 text-xs text-gray-500">
          Fees and requirements shown are based on our most recent review. Always verify current information at the <a href="https://www.sos.state.tx.us" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-teal-700 underline hover:text-teal-900">Texas Secretary of State website</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Affiliate Disclosure -->
    <div class="mb-10 rounded-xl border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50/50 p-4 text-xs leading-relaxed text-gray-600">
      {siteConfig.disclosureText}
    </div>

    <!-- Why Texas -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Why Form an LLC in Texas?</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          Texas is consistently ranked among the top states for business formation. With a population exceeding 30 million and a gross state product that rivals many countries, the Lone Star State offers entrepreneurs a massive market and a supportive business environment.
        </p>
        <p>
          Key advantages of forming a Texas LLC include:
        </p>
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li><strong>No state income tax:</strong> Texas does not impose a personal income tax, which means LLC members who live in Texas keep more of their pass-through income.</li>
          <li><strong>Favorable franchise tax threshold:</strong> Texas LLCs with total revenue below $2.47 million (as of our last review) owe no franchise tax. Many small businesses fall below this threshold.</li>
          <li><strong>No annual report:</strong> Unlike many states, Texas does not require an annual report filing, reducing your ongoing compliance burden.</li>
          <li><strong>Strong legal protections:</strong> Texas provides solid personal liability protection for LLC members and has well-established business law.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Steps -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Steps to Form Your Texas LLC</h2>

      <div class="mt-8 space-y-8">

        <!-- Step 1 -->
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#0d9488] text-sm font-bold text-white">1</span>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">Choose a Name for Your Texas LLC</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">
            <p>
              Your LLC name must be distinguishable from all other business entities registered in Texas. It must include "Limited Liability Company," "LLC," or "L.L.C." at the end.
            </p>
            <p>
              You can search for available names using the Texas Secretary of State's SOSDirect database. If you find the perfect name but are not ready to file, you can reserve it for 120 days by filing a name reservation application with a $40 fee.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Tips for choosing a name:</strong></p>
            <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-1">
              <li>Check that a matching domain name is available for your website.</li>
              <li>Make sure the name does not infringe on existing trademarks (search the USPTO database).</li>
              <li>Avoid restricted words like "bank," "insurance," or "university" unless you have the required licenses.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 2 -->
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#0d9488] text-sm font-bold text-white">2</span>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">Appoint a Registered Agent</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">
            <p>
              Texas requires every LLC to designate a registered agent. This is a person or business entity authorized to receive legal documents, government correspondence, and service of process on behalf of your LLC.
            </p>
            <p>
              Your registered agent must have a physical street address in Texas (P.O. boxes are not accepted) and be available during normal business hours.
            </p>
            <p>
              You can serve as your own registered agent, but many business owners prefer to use a professional registered agent service for privacy and reliability. Most LLC formation services include at least one year of registered agent service.
            </p>
            <p>
              See our <a href="/best-llc-services/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">best LLC services</a> for providers that include registered agent service with formation.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 3 -->
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#0d9488] text-sm font-bold text-white">3</span>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">File a Certificate of Formation</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">
            <p>
              In Texas, the formation document for an LLC is called the Certificate of Formation (Form 205). You file this with the Texas Secretary of State. The filing fee is <strong>$300</strong>.
            </p>
            <p>
              You can file online through the SOSDirect system or by mail. Online filing is faster, with typical processing times of a few business days. Mail filings can take several weeks.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Information you will need:</strong></p>
            <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-1">
              <li>LLC name</li>
              <li>Registered agent name and address</li>
              <li>Whether the LLC is member-managed or manager-managed</li>
              <li>Names and addresses of governing persons (managers or members)</li>
              <li>The LLC's purpose (a general statement is acceptable)</li>
              <li>Duration of the LLC (perpetual is the default)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 4 -->
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#0d9488] text-sm font-bold text-white">4</span>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">Create an Operating Agreement</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">
            <p>
              Texas does not legally require an operating agreement, but creating one is strongly recommended for every LLC. This internal document defines the ownership structure, member roles, profit-sharing arrangements, voting procedures, and what happens if a member leaves.
            </p>
            <p>
              Without an operating agreement, your LLC defaults to the rules in the Texas Business Organizations Code, which may not match your intentions. An operating agreement also helps establish your LLC as a separate legal entity, which strengthens your personal liability protection.
            </p>
            <p>
              Learn more in our <a href="/learn/llc-operating-agreement/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">guide to LLC operating agreements</a>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 5 -->
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#0d9488] text-sm font-bold text-white">5</span>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">Get an EIN (Employer Identification Number)</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">
            <p>
              An EIN is essentially a Social Security number for your business. You will need one to open a business bank account, hire employees, and file federal taxes. Applying for an EIN is free and can be done online through the IRS website in a matter of minutes.
            </p>
            <p>
              If your LLC has more than one member, an EIN is required. Even single-member LLCs benefit from having one, as it keeps your personal Social Security number off business documents and bank accounts.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Texas Franchise Tax -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Texas Franchise Tax</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          While Texas has no state income tax, it does impose a franchise tax (also called a margin tax) on most businesses, including LLCs. However, there is a generous "no tax due" threshold.
        </p>
        <p>
          As of our most recent review, Texas LLCs with total revenue at or below <strong>$2.47 million</strong> owe no franchise tax. You must still file a franchise tax report each year (due May 15), but if you are below the threshold, you simply file a "no tax due" report.
        </p>
        <p>
          For LLCs above the threshold, the tax rate is generally 0.375% for retail and wholesale businesses and 0.75% for other businesses, calculated on the LLC's taxable margin. You can calculate your taxable margin using one of four methods: total revenue minus cost of goods sold, total revenue minus compensation, 70% of total revenue, or total revenue minus $1 million.
        </p>
        <p>
          Your first franchise tax report is due May 15 of the year following the calendar year in which your LLC was formed. For example, if you form your LLC in August 2026, your first franchise tax report is due May 15, 2027.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">
          Franchise tax thresholds and rates can change. Verify the current figures with the <a href="https://comptroller.texas.gov/taxes/franchise/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-teal-700 underline hover:text-teal-900">Texas Comptroller website</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Costs Breakdown -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Texas LLC Costs Breakdown</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>Understanding the full cost of forming and maintaining a Texas LLC helps you budget accurately. Here is a breakdown of the common fees you can expect:</p>
        <div class="mt-4 overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="min-w-full border border-gray-200 text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="bg-gray-50">
                <th class="border-b border-gray-200 px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900">Fee</th>
                <th class="border-b border-gray-200 px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900">Cost</th>
                <th class="border-b border-gray-200 px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900">Frequency</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-200">
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Certificate of Formation (Form 205)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$300</td><td class="px-4 py-3">One-time</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Name Reservation (optional)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$40</td><td class="px-4 py-3">One-time (120 days)</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Registered Agent Service</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$0 - $299/year</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Annual</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Franchise Tax Report</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$0 (if below threshold)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Annual (May 15)</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">EIN (Federal Tax ID)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Free</td><td class="px-4 py-3">One-time</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Certified Copy of Formation</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$30</td><td class="px-4 py-3">As needed</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Certificate of Good Standing</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$15</td><td class="px-4 py-3">As needed</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">DBA / Assumed Name Filing</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Varies by county</td><td class="px-4 py-3">One-time</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p>
          Using an <a href="/best-llc-services/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">LLC formation service</a> typically costs between $0 and $299 on top of the state filing fee. Many services include registered agent coverage in their packages, which can save you money in the long run compared to hiring an agent separately.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Tax Considerations -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Texas LLC Tax Considerations</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          One of the biggest advantages of forming an LLC in Texas is the favorable tax environment. Here is what you need to know about each type of tax that may apply to your Texas LLC:
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mt-6">Federal Income Tax</h3>
        <p>
          By default, a single-member Texas LLC is treated as a disregarded entity for federal tax purposes, meaning income passes through to your personal tax return (Schedule C of Form 1040). A multi-member LLC is treated as a partnership and files Form 1065. Members report their share of profits on their personal returns. Alternatively, you can elect to have your LLC taxed as an S-Corp or C-Corp by filing the appropriate IRS forms if it benefits your tax situation.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mt-6">Self-Employment Tax</h3>
        <p>
          LLC members who actively participate in the business typically owe self-employment tax (Social Security and Medicare) at a rate of 15.3% on net earnings. This applies regardless of which state you form in. If your LLC generates substantial income, electing S-Corp taxation can potentially reduce self-employment taxes by allowing you to pay yourself a reasonable salary and take remaining profits as distributions.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mt-6">Sales and Use Tax</h3>
        <p>
          Texas imposes a 6.25% state sales tax on most tangible personal property and some services. Local jurisdictions may add up to 2% on top of that, bringing the combined rate to a maximum of 8.25%. If your LLC sells taxable goods or services, you must register for a sales tax permit with the Texas Comptroller, collect sales tax from customers, and remit it to the state on the required schedule (monthly, quarterly, or annually depending on your volume).
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mt-6">Property Tax</h3>
        <p>
          If your LLC owns real property or tangible business personal property (equipment, inventory, furniture), you may owe property taxes to your local county appraisal district. Texas has no state property tax, but local rates can be significant. Make sure to render (report) your business personal property to your county by April 15 each year.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Foreign LLC Registration -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Registering a Foreign LLC in Texas</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          If your LLC was formed in another state but you conduct business in Texas, you must register as a foreign LLC with the Texas Secretary of State. "Foreign" in this context simply means out-of-state, not international.
        </p>
        <p>
          To register a foreign LLC in Texas, you file an Application for Registration (Form 304) with the Secretary of State. The filing fee is $750, which is significantly higher than the domestic formation fee. You will also need a registered agent with a physical address in Texas.
        </p>
        <p>
          Activities that generally require foreign LLC registration include maintaining an office or employees in Texas, holding regular business meetings in the state, owning property in Texas, or entering into contracts that will be performed within the state.
        </p>
        <p>
          Conducting business in Texas without registering as a foreign LLC can result in penalties, inability to use Texas courts to enforce contracts, and accrual of back fees.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Timeline -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">How Long Does It Take to Form a Texas LLC?</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          The timeline for forming a Texas LLC depends primarily on how you choose to file:
        </p>
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Online filing (SOSDirect):</strong> Typically processed within two to three business days. This is the fastest method for most filers.</li>
          <li><strong>Mail filing:</strong> Processing times can range from one to three weeks, depending on the volume of filings the Secretary of State's office is handling.</li>
          <li><strong>Using a formation service:</strong> Professional services such as <a href="/reviews/zenbusiness/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">ZenBusiness</a> or <a href="/reviews/northwest-registered-agent/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">Northwest Registered Agent</a> typically submit filings within one business day of placing your order and can offer expedited processing.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          After your Certificate of Formation is approved, you can immediately proceed with obtaining your EIN, opening a bank account, and beginning business operations. The EIN process through the IRS website is instant during business hours.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Common Mistakes -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Common Mistakes When Forming a Texas LLC</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>Avoid these frequent errors that new LLC owners make in Texas:</p>
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Forgetting the franchise tax report:</strong> Even if your LLC owes no tax, you must still file the annual franchise tax report by May 15. Failure to file can result in penalties and eventually forfeiture of your LLC's right to do business in Texas.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping the operating agreement:</strong> While not legally required, operating without one exposes you to default state rules that may not suit your business. It also weakens your liability protection. Read our <a href="/learn/llc-operating-agreement/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">operating agreement guide</a> for details.</li>
          <li><strong>Mixing personal and business finances:</strong> Commingling funds is one of the fastest ways to lose your LLC's liability protection through what is called "piercing the corporate veil."</li>
          <li><strong>Not checking name availability first:</strong> Filing a Certificate of Formation with a name that is already in use will result in rejection and delay.</li>
          <li><strong>Choosing the wrong management structure:</strong> Texas allows member-managed and manager-managed LLCs. The choice affects who can sign contracts and make decisions for the LLC. Consider your needs carefully before filing.</li>
          <li><strong>Neglecting local permits:</strong> Many Texas cities and counties require separate business permits or licenses. Check with your local municipality before starting operations.</li>
          <li><strong>Using a P.O. Box for the registered agent:</strong> Texas requires a physical street address for the registered agent. A P.O. Box will cause your filing to be rejected.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Industry Considerations -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Industry-Specific Considerations in Texas</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>Texas has a diverse economy, and certain industries have specific requirements or advantages when forming an LLC:</p>
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Oil and gas:</strong> Texas is the largest oil-producing state. LLCs in this sector should be aware of the Texas Railroad Commission regulations, severance taxes on production, and specific environmental compliance requirements.</li>
          <li><strong>Real estate:</strong> Many Texas real estate investors use LLCs to hold properties for liability protection. Each property can be held in a separate LLC (known as a series LLC strategy). Texas allows Series LLCs, which let you create separate "cells" under one umbrella LLC.</li>
          <li><strong>Technology:</strong> Texas, particularly the Austin area, has become a major technology hub. Tech startups forming LLCs should consider intellectual property protections and whether a future conversion to a corporation might be needed for venture capital funding.</li>
          <li><strong>Food and beverage:</strong> Restaurants, food trucks, and beverage companies must obtain health permits and food handler certifications in addition to their LLC formation. The Texas Department of State Health Services oversees food establishment licensing.</li>
          <li><strong>Construction:</strong> Contractors in Texas may need to register with local licensing boards. While Texas does not have a state-level general contractor license, many cities and counties require their own permits and licenses.</li>
          <li><strong>Professional services:</strong> Certain professions in Texas (such as attorneys, architects, and engineers) cannot form a standard LLC but must instead form a Professional LLC (PLLC) with the Texas Secretary of State.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- After Formation -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">After You Form Your Texas LLC</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>Once your LLC is officially formed, take these additional steps to set your business up for success:</p>
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Open a business bank account:</strong> Keep personal and business finances separate to maintain your liability protection. Most banks require your Certificate of Formation, EIN confirmation letter, and a photo ID.</li>
          <li><strong>Obtain necessary licenses and permits:</strong> Check with your city and county for local business license requirements. Some industries require state-level licenses as well.</li>
          <li><strong>File your franchise tax report:</strong> Even if you owe no tax, you must file an annual report with the Texas Comptroller by May 15.</li>
          <li><strong>Get a sales tax permit:</strong> If you plan to sell taxable goods or services, register with the Texas Comptroller for a sales tax permit before making your first sale.</li>
          <li><strong>Create your operating agreement:</strong> Finalize and sign your <a href="/learn/llc-operating-agreement/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">LLC operating agreement</a> with all members.</li>
          <li><strong>Consider business insurance:</strong> General liability insurance, professional liability insurance, or other coverage depending on your industry.</li>
          <li><strong>Set up accounting and bookkeeping:</strong> Use accounting software or hire a bookkeeper to track income, expenses, and maintain clean financial records from day one.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep records:</strong> Maintain detailed records of financial transactions, member meetings, and major business decisions.</li>
          <li><strong>Register your DBA if needed:</strong> If you plan to operate under a name different from your official LLC name, file an assumed name certificate with the county clerk in each county where you do business.</li>
          <li><strong>Build business credit:</strong> Open a business credit card, establish vendor accounts that report to credit bureaus, and keep your business finances in good standing to build a strong credit profile for your LLC.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Advantages and Disadvantages -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Advantages and Disadvantages of a Texas LLC</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900">Advantages</h3>
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li>No personal state income tax means more take-home profit for LLC members.</li>
          <li>No annual report filing requirement (only the franchise tax report).</li>
          <li>Generous franchise tax threshold means most small LLCs pay zero state business tax.</li>
          <li>Strong economy and large consumer market across multiple industries.</li>
          <li>Series LLC option available for real estate investors and multi-venture entrepreneurs.</li>
          <li>Business-friendly court system and established case law for LLCs.</li>
        </ul>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mt-6">Disadvantages</h3>
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li>The $300 filing fee is higher than many other states.</li>
          <li>The franchise tax, while often zero for small businesses, adds complexity with annual filing requirements.</li>
          <li>The $750 foreign LLC registration fee is one of the highest in the country.</li>
          <li>Texas does not have as strong privacy protections as states like Delaware, Wyoming, or New Mexico.</li>
          <li>Property taxes are among the highest in the nation, which impacts LLCs that own real estate or significant business personal property.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Frequently Asked Questions About Texas LLCs</h2>
      <div class="mt-6 space-y-6">
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">How much does it cost to start an LLC in Texas?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">The state filing fee for a Texas LLC is $300. Additional costs may include a registered agent service ($0-$299 per year), an optional name reservation ($40), and any professional formation service fees. Many LLC formation services offer packages starting from $0 plus the state fee.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">Do I need to live in Texas to form a Texas LLC?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">No. Anyone can form an LLC in Texas regardless of where they live. However, you will need a registered agent with a physical address in Texas. If you do not live in Texas and do not have a physical presence there, consider whether forming in your home state might be simpler and less expensive overall.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">Does Texas require an annual report for LLCs?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">Texas does not require a traditional annual report. However, you must file an annual franchise tax report with the Texas Comptroller by May 15 each year, even if your LLC owes no franchise tax. This is functionally similar to an annual report in other states.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">What is the Texas franchise tax threshold?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">As of our last review, Texas LLCs with total annual revenue at or below $2.47 million owe no franchise tax. You still need to file a "no tax due" report. The threshold is adjusted periodically, so check with the Texas Comptroller for the most current figure.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">Can I be my own registered agent in Texas?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">Yes, you can serve as your own registered agent as long as you have a physical street address in Texas (not a P.O. Box) and are available during normal business hours. However, many business owners prefer a professional service for privacy and reliability. See our <a href="/reviews/northwest-registered-agent/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">Northwest Registered Agent review</a> for a top-rated option.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">How long does it take to get a Texas LLC approved?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">Online filings through SOSDirect are typically processed within two to three business days. Mail filings can take one to three weeks. Using a professional formation service can sometimes speed up the process since they submit filings promptly and correctly the first time.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">What is a Series LLC in Texas?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">Texas permits the formation of a Series LLC, which allows you to create multiple "series" or cells within a single LLC. Each series can have its own assets, members, and liabilities that are legally separate from the other series. This is particularly popular among real estate investors who want to hold multiple properties under one umbrella without forming separate LLCs for each.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">Do I need a business license to operate my Texas LLC?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">Texas does not have a general state business license. However, many cities and counties require local business permits, and certain industries require specific state licenses (such as contractors, food service operators, and healthcare providers). Check with your local municipality and industry regulatory body to determine what permits you need.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">Can a Texas LLC be taxed as an S-Corp?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">Yes. A Texas LLC can elect S-Corp taxation by filing IRS Form 2553. This can provide tax savings for LLC members who earn significant income, as it allows you to split income between a reasonable salary (subject to self-employment tax) and distributions (which are not). Consult a tax professional to determine if S-Corp election makes sense for your situation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">What happens if I do not file my Texas franchise tax report?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">If you fail to file your franchise tax report by the May 15 deadline, the Texas Comptroller may impose penalties and interest. Continued failure to file can eventually result in your LLC's right to transact business being forfeited. You can reinstate a forfeited LLC, but there are additional fees and back-filing requirements involved.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

